   <p>
        <span class="docSource"><span class="dType"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr></span> (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Massachusetts Historical Society ]">MHi</span>:Warren-Adams Coll.); addressed: To the Hon. James Warren Esqr Speaker of the House and Pay Master General Watertown favd. by Mr Tracy; docketed: Mr. J: A Lettr Octr 12. 1775; with enclosure in <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>s hand.</span>
       </p>

      </div>
      <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA03d115n1-ptr" id="PJA03d115n1">1</a>
       
   <p>The Dutch States-General, under pressure from Great Britain, had on 20 March ordered that no munitions be exported to the North American continent for six months, an order which was subsequently renewed periodically, but which was not obeyed in the Dutch West Indies during the American Revolution (F. C. Van Oosten, Some Notes Concerning the Dutch West Indies During the American Revolutionary War, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">The American Neptune</span>, 36:156 [July 1976]).</p>

